79\u201380; ''X-Factor'' #49\u201350; ''Damage Control'' #1\u20134; and ''Web of Spider-Man'' #64\u201365\n| August 2011\n| {{ISBNT|978-0-7851-4488-5}}\n|-\n| ''Cable and the New Mutants''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #86\u201394, ''New Mutants Annual #5''\n| January 2011\n| {{ISBNT|0785149708}}\n|-\n| ''Cable Classic, Volume 1''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #87; ''Cable: Blood and Metal'' #1\u20132; ''Cable'' #1\u20134\n| March 2008\n| {{ISBNT|078513123X}}\n|-\n| ''X-Men: X-Tinction Agenda''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #95\u201397; ''Uncanny X-Men'' #270\u2013272; ''X-Factor'' #60\u201362\n| November 1991\n| {{ISBNT|0871359227}}\n|-\n| ''X-Men: X-Tinction Agenda'' (Hardcover edition)\n| ''New Mutants'' #95\u201397; ''Uncanny X-Men'' #235\u2013238 & #270\u2013272; ''X-Factor'' (1986) #60\u201362\n| August 2011\n| {{ISBNT|978-0785155317}}\n|-\n| ''Deadpool Classic, Volume 1''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #98; ''[[Deadpool]]'' (\"The Circle Chase\") #1\u20134; ''Deadpool'', vol. 2 (\"Sins of the Past\") #1\u20134; ''Deadpool'', vol. 3 #1\n| May 2008\n| {{ISBNT|0785131248}}\n|-\n| ''X-Force: Shatterstar''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #99\u2013100; ''X-Force: Shatterstar'' #1\u20134\n| August 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0785116338}}\n|-\n| ''X-Force: A Force to be Reckoned With''\n| ''The New Mutants'' #98\u2013100, ''X-Force'' #1\u20134, ''Spider-Man'' #16\n| January 2011\n| {{ISBNT|978-0785149842}}\n|}\n\n== ''The New Mutants'', volume 2 ==\n{{Infobox comics organization <!-- Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics -->\n| name = New Mutants (Training Squad)\n| image = Newmutants2.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption = The New Mutants from ''New X-Men: Academy X'' #2 by Randy Green. From left to right: Danielle Moonstar, Surge, Prodigy, Wind Dancer, Elixir, Wallflower.\n| publisher = [[Marvel Comics]]\n| debut = ''New X-Men: Academy X'' #2 (August 2004)\n| creators = [[Nunzio DeFilippis]]<br />[[Christina Weir]]<br />[[Keron Grant]]<br />Randy Green\n| base = [[X-Mansion|Xavier Institute for Higher Learning]]\n| members = [[Danielle Moonstar]] (advisor)<br />[[Elixir (comics)|Elixir]]<br />[[Icarus (comics)|Icarus]]<br />[[Prodigy (David Alleyne)|Prodigy]]<br />[[Surge (comics)|Surge]]<br />[[Wallflower (comics)|Wallflower]]<br />[[Wind Dancer]]<br />[[Wither (comics)|Wither]]\n| subcat = Marvel Comics\n| hero = y\n| sortkey = New Mutants\n}}\n{{Main|New X-Men}}\nThe second incarnation of the ''New Mutants'' debuted in 2003 with an ongoing series of the same name, written by [[Nunzio DeFilippis]] and [[Christina Weir]]. The series would continue for 13 issues, until June 2004, before being relaunched as ''[[New X-Men|New X-Men: Academy X]]'' in July 2004, with a new #1.\n\nThe series featured a handful of the dozens of mutant teenagers attending the [[X-Mansion|Xavier Institute]], as well as their instructors, which included various [[X-Men]] as well as former members of the original New Mutants ([[Karma (comics)|Karma]], [[Magma (comics)|Magma]], [[Danielle Moonstar|Dani Moonstar]], and [[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]]).\n\nThe featured group of students never refer to themselves as \"the New Mutants\" before the series relaunch as ''New X-Men: Academy X'' in 2004, and the reorganization of the Xavier Institute student body into various training squads. The New Mutants, advised by Dani Moonstar, were:\n\n* '''[[Elixir (comics)|Elixir]]''' (Josh Foley) \u2013 Josh is an [[Mutant (Marvel Comics)#Omega-level mutants|Omega-Level mutant]] who can manipulate his or others' biologies to heal or harm. In addition, Elixir possesses gold skin which converts to black when he uses his powers offensively. He was one of the 27 students at the Xavier Institute to retain his powers after \"M-Day\".  He was seemingly killed by the [[Dark Riders (comics)|Dark Riders]] before returning with vastly enhanced abilities.  He is currently taking refuge in Tibet with [[Shen Xorn|Xorn]].\n* '''[[Icarus (comics)|Icarus]]''' (Joshua \"Jay\" Guthrie) \u2013 Jay possesses red angelic wings on his back that allow him to fly and which grant him an accelerated healing process. Furthermore, he possesses the ability to manipulate his own voice. He was one of the 27 students at the Xavier Institute to retain his powers after \"M-Day\". Jay's wings are amputated by [[William Stryker|Stryker]],<ref>''New X-Men'' vol. 2, #23 (April 2006)</ref> who later kills him.<ref>''New X-Men'' vol. 2, #27 (August 2006)</ref>\n* '''[[Prodigy (David Alleyne)|Prodigy]]''' (David Alleyne) \u2013 David was the team's co-leader who could temporarily gain the knowledge and skills of those near him. Although he was de-powered after \"M-Day\", he has retained all the knowledge he had acquired prior to the \"Decimation\".<ref>''New X-Men'' vol. 2, #43 (December 2007)</ref> Current member of the Young Avengers.\n* '''[[Surge (comics)|Surge]]''' (Noriko Ashida) \u2013 Noriko is [[Japanese people|Japanese]]. She absorbs electricity from her environment which she can discharge as powerful electric blasts or utilize as superhuman speed. She requires mechanical gauntlets to prevent overcharge. Surge was one of the 27 students at the [[X-Mansion|Xavier Institute]] to retain her powers after \"M-Day\". She is currently a student of the Jean Grey School for Higher Learning.\n* '''[[Wallflower (comics)|Wallflower]]''' (Laurie Collins) \u2013 Laurie is a shy girl who generates highly potent [[pheromone]]s that influence people's emotions. She was one of the 27 students at the Xavier Institute to retain her powers after \"M-Day\". Laurie was later killed by one of [[William Stryker|Stryker]]'s men.<ref>''New X-Men'' vol. 2, #25 (June 2006)</ref>\n* '''[[Wind Dancer]]''' (Sofia Mantega) \u2013 Sofia was the other co-leader and was a temperamental aerokinetic who was particularly adept at using this power to manipulate sound. She was depowered after \"M-Day\" and joined a group of fellow ex-mutants as part of the [[New Warriors]].  Donning a variety of mechanical gear, she took up the codename Renascence before the group disbanded.  Her current whereabouts are unknown.\n* '''[[Wither (comics)|Wither]]''' (Kevin Ford) \u2013 Kevin could cause organic material to decay with his touch. He eventually switches to the [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellions]] squad.<ref>''New X-Men: Academy X'' #6 (December 2004)</ref> He is later killed by Elixir.<ref>''X-Force'' vol. 3, #25 (Released March 2010, Published May 2010)</ref>\n\nAnother such group, advised by Emma Frost, was known as the [[Hellions (Marvel Comics)|Hellions]] and, like their predecessor, was the arch-rival of the New Mutants. Whereas the original ''New Mutants'' series revolved around battles with world-threatening menaces, ''New Mutants'' volume 2 focused on the characters' personal relationships and struggles with controlling their powers.\n\nAfter \"[[Decimation (comics)|M-Day]]\", the cataclysmic event that decimated the world's mutant population, only 27 of the 182 students enrolled at the Xavier Institute retained their powers. The New Mutants and the other training squads were disbanded, and the remaining students were folded into a single junior team, the New X-Men.<ref>''New X-Men'' vol 2, #23 (April 2006)</ref>\n\n===Volume 2 cast===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n|+Members of the New Mutants\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Issues\n! scope=\"col\" | Characters\n|-\n| #1\n| {{hlist|[[Danielle Moonstar]]|[[Wind Dancer]]{{efn|group=lower-a|As Sofia Montega}}}}\n|-\n| #2\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|[[Hellion (Marvel Comics)|Hellion]]{{efn|group=lower-b|As Julian Keller until issue #9}}|[[Wallflower (comics)|Wallflower]]{{efn|group=lower-c|As Laurie Collins}}|Wind Dancer}}\n|-\n| #3\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|Hellion|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|[[Wither (comics)|Wither]]{{efn|group=lower-d|As Kevin Ford}}}}\n|-\n| #4\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|[[Karma (comics)|Karma]]|[[Prodigy (David Alleyne)|Prodigy]]{{efn|group=lower-e|As David Alleyne}}}}\n|-\n| #5\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|[[Elixir (comics)|Elixir]]{{efn|group=lower-f|As Josh Foley}}|Hellion|Karma|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|Wither}}\n|-\n| #6\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|Elixir|Karma|Prodigy|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|Wither}}\n|-\n| #7&ndash;8\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|Elixir|Hellion|Karma|Prodigy|Wallflower|Wind Dancer}}\n|-\n| #9&ndash;10\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|Elixir|Hellion|Karma|Prodigy|[[Surge (comics)|Surge]]{{efn|group=lower-g|As Noriko Ashida}}|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|[[Wolfsbane (comics)|Wolfsbane]]}}\n|-\n| #11\n| {{hlist|Elixir|Wallflower|Wolfsbane}}\n|-\n| #12\n| {{hlist|Danielle Moonstar|Elixir|Hellion|Karma|Prodigy|Surge|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|Wolfsbane}}\n|-\n| #13\n| {{hlist|[[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]]|Danielle Moonstar|Elixir|Karma|[[Magma (comics)|Magma]]|Prodigy|Surge|[[Sunspot (comics)|Sunspot]]|Wallflower|Wind Dancer|Wolfsbane}}\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Notelist}}\n\n===Volume 2 collected editions===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+''New Mutants'' volume 2 collected editions\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected !! Publication date !! ISBN\n|-\n| ''New Mutants: Back to School''\n| ''New Mutants,'' vol. 2 #1\u20136\n| March 2005\n| {{ISBNT|0785112421}}\n|-\n| ''New Mutants: Back to School \u2013 Complete Collection''\n| ''New Mutants,'' vol. 2 #1\u201313; ''X-Men Unlimited'' #42\u201343\n| January 2018\n| {{ISBNT|978-1302910327}}\n|-\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n== ''New Mutants'', volume 3 ==\n{{Infobox comics organization <!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n|name= New Mutants\n|image= New Mutants (vol.3) 1 cover.jpg\n|imagesize= 250\n|caption= Variant cover to ''New Mutants,'' vol. 3 #1 by [[Bob McLeod (comics)|Bob McLeod]].\n|publisher= [[Marvel Comics]]\n|debut= ''New Mutants'' #1 (2009)\n|creators= [[Zeb Wells]] (writer)<br />Diogenes Neves (artist)\n|base= [[Asteroid M#Fifth version/Utopia|Utopia]]<br />1128 Mission Street, [[San Francisco]]\n|members='''Former Members:'''<br />[[Blink (comics)|Blink]]<br />[[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]]<br />[[Cypher (comics)|Cypher]]<br />[[Karma (comics)|Karma]]<br />[[Magik (Illyana Rasputin)|Magik]]<br />[[Magma (comics)|Magma]]<br />[[Danielle Moonstar|Mirage]]<br />[[Sunspot (comics)|Sunspot]]<br />[[Warlock (New Mutants)|Warlock]]<br />[[Nate Grey|X-Man]]\n|subcat=\n|hero=\n|villain=\n}}\n\nIn May 2009, a third volume of ''New Mutants'' was launched. The series was initially written by [[Zeb Wells]] and pencilled by Diogenes Neves with the titular characters forming a new field team for the [[X-Men]]. The team is a reunion of the cast from the first volume, consisting of [[Cannonball (comics)|Cannonball]], [[Karma (comics)|Karma]], [[Magik (Illyana Rasputin)|Magik]], [[Magma (comics)|Magma]], [[Dani Moonstar]] and  [[Sunspot (comics)|Sunspot]].\n\nThe reunion is spun from events from the limited series ''[[X-Infernus]]''. Magik shows up at the X-Men headquarters in San Francisco, claiming to be from the future and warning that Dani Moonstar and Karma are in danger. Once tests show that Illyanna is not an imposter, Cannonball leads a rescue mission with her. They are joined by Magma and Sunspot.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #1 (July 2009)</ref> They end up taking on [[Legion (Marvel Comics)|Legion]].\n\nIn later issue, Warlock returns to Earth<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #5 (Released September 2009, Published November 2009)</ref> and Cypher reappears alive, under the control of [[Selene (comics)|Selene]]. After Warlock frees him from Selene's control, Cypher joins the team.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #6 (Released October 2009, Published December 2009)</ref><ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #8 (Released December 2009, Published February 2010)</ref>\n\nDuring \"[[Siege (comics)|Siege]]\", [[Hela (comics)|Hela]] empowers Dani (now going by the codename Mirage<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #10 (Released February 2010, Published April 2010)</ref>) as a Valkyrie to bring the souls of the fallen [[Asgard (comics)|Asgardians]] to her. During \"[[X-Men: Second Coming]]\", Karma loses her leg after being repeatedly stabbed by [[Cameron Hodge]].<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #13 (Released May 2010, Published July 2010)</ref> It is replaced with a bionic one.\n\nMagik leads the team to [[Otherplace|Limbo]], as part of her plan for revenge against the Elder Gods. [[Cyclops (Marvel Comics)|Cyclops]] has her imprisoned for her actions.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #25 (Released May 2011, Published July 2011)</ref> In the same issue, Cannonball and Karma also leave the team.\n\nAfter they successfully rescue him from [[Sugar Man]], [[Nate Grey]] joins the team.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #28 (Published July 2011, Released September 2011)</ref>\n\nWhen the X-Men split in ''[[X-Men: Schism]]'', the team sides with Cyclops and stays on Utopia.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #33 (Published November 2011, Released January 2012)</ref> Their next mission is to find [[Blink (comics)|Blink]]. After locating her and helping her defeat a mutant rock band (Diskhord), Blink returns with them but decides to join the X-Men at the [[X-Mansion|Jean Grey School of Higher Learning]].<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #36 (Published January 2012, Released March 2012)</ref> She does join them during the last issues of the series.<ref>''New Mutants'' vol. 3, #45 (Published July 2012, Released September 2012)</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Collected editions of ''New Mutants'' Volume 3\n|-\n! Title !! Material collected !! Publication date !! ISBN\n|-\n| ''New Mutants: Return of Legion''\n| ''New Mutants'', vol. 3 #1\u20135; ''Marvel Spotlight: New Mutants''\n| December 2009\n| {{ISBNT|0785139923}}\n|-\n| ''New Mutants: Necrosha''\n| ''New Mutants'', vol. 3 #6\u201311\n| May 2010\n| {{ISBNT|0785139931}}\n|-\n| ''X-Necrosha''\n| ''New X-Men'' #32; ''X-Force'' vol. 3 #11, #21\u201325; ''New Mutants'' vol. 3 #6\u20138; ''X-Men: Legacy'' #231\u2013234; ''X-Force/New Mutants: Necrosha One-Shot''; ''X Necrosha: The Gathering''; material from ''X-Force vol. 3 Annual #1''\n| December 2010\n| {{ISBNT|078514675X}}\n|-\